---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "Learning";
const description = "How I trained my judgment through sustained study and applied practice.";
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <section class="section learning-hero" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <p class="eyebrow">Learning as method</p>
    <h1>Learning</h1>
    <p class="intro-lead">
      I follow where the questions get harder. Since 1992, I’ve returned to structured learning alongside my work. Not for credentials. For constraint. The goal has been consistent: sharpen how I think when decisions carry consequence.
    </p>

    <div class="decision-grid" aria-label="Learning paths">
      <a class="decision-card" href="#formal-learning">
        <span>Formal Study</span>
        <p>Structured learning across Oklahoma State, Stanford, Stanford ICME, and MIT.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="decision-card" href="#field-learning">
        <span>Field Learning</span>
        <p>Observation and practice drawn from teams, users, civic systems, and real contexts.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="decision-card" href="#proof">
        <span>Work Translation</span>
        <p>How learning becomes judgment, interpretation, accountability, and system design.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="formal-learning" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Formal Study</h2>
      <p>The throughline is not a transcript. It is a pattern of returning to structured environments when the questions required more precision.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="foundation-grid">
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Oklahoma State University</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">1992–1994</p>
        <p>Early study established the pattern. I was drawn to environments that forced clarity, even before I knew where it would lead.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Stanford University</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">2005</p>
        <p>I brought my team at Yahoo! into a course focused on improvisation. The objective wasn’t performance. It was collaboration: learning how to build on each other’s thinking, articulate ideas in motion, and design without shutting down possibility.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Stanford ICME</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">2016</p>
        <p>Coursework marked a deliberate turn toward data and systems. I focused on how decisions get made when information is incomplete, and how reasoning breaks under pressure.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>MIT</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">2017–today</p>
        <p>Sustained study through MIT programs has focused on design, AI, and decision systems. This work has been self-directed and ongoing, built on repetition rather than milestones.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="field-learning" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Learning in the Field</h2>
      <p>Some of the most useful learning happens outside a classroom, where behavior is visible and assumptions have nowhere elegant to hide.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="theme-grid">
      <article class="theme-card">
        <h3>Evernote</h3>
        <p>We observed preschool children fingerpaint to understand how people explore color without constraint. That work informed how palettes could behave in a digital product, shifting from rigid selection to fluid exploration.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="theme-card">
        <h3>Yahoo!</h3>
        <p>Through improvisation training at Stanford, we practiced building on each other’s ideas in real time. It reshaped how I think about collaboration: systems should extend thinking, not shut it down.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="theme-card">
        <h3>Civic Systems</h3>
        <p>Work in election environments reinforced how systems behave under pressure. Procedures matter, but interpretation determines whether participation and trust hold.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="proof" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>How It Shows Up in the Work</h2>
      <p>Learning only matters here if it changes how decisions are designed, challenged, and made accountable.</p>
    </div>

    <article class="entry">
      <h3>Separate signal from output</h3>
      <p>I look past what a system returns and ask what the output actually means under real conditions.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="entry">
      <h3>Design for interpretation</h3>
      <p>I build for the human layer where uncertainty, escalation, and judgment determine whether a system holds.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="entry">
      <h3>Stay accountable when wrong</h3>
      <p>I treat failure as expected, not exceptional, and design systems that can be challenged, corrected, and trusted again.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="section learning-close" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <p>
      I don’t use learning to expand what I know. I use it to reduce how often I’m wrong in systems that matter.
    </p>
    <p>
      Learning is still active. Today it meant explaining equatorial storms and jet streams to my six-year-old.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .eyebrow {
    margin: 0 0 12px;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--secondary);
  }

  .intro-lead {
    max-width: 42rem;
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    line-height: 1.58;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .decision-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 14px;
    margin-top: 34px;
    max-width: 56rem;
  }

  .decision-card {
    display: block;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding: 18px;
    text-decoration: none;
    color: inherit;
    transition: border-color 0.2s ease, transform 0.2s ease;
  }

  .decision-card:hover,
  .decision-card:focus-visible {
    border-color: var(--text);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  .decision-card span {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    line-height: 1;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--text);
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    font-weight: 600;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .decision-card p {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.45;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .section-heading {
    margin-bottom: 44px;
  }

  .section-heading h2 {
    margin: 0 0 22px;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.3;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--secondary);
  }

  .section-heading p {
    margin: 0 0 20px;
    max-width: 38rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .foundation-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 16px;
    max-width: 56rem;
  }

  .foundation-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .foundation-card h3 {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 0 0 4px;
    color: var(--title);
  }

  .foundation-card p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .theme-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 16px;
  }

  .theme-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .theme-card h3 {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    margin: 0 0 8px;
  }

  .theme-card p {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--text);
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .entry h3 {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 0 0 4px;
  }

  .learning-close p:last-child {
    max-width: 42rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .decision-grid,
    .foundation-grid,
    .theme-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
</Layout>
